<TutorialLayout title="GSD on an Existing Codebase" description="Use GSD to plan and build a feature in a large, unfamiliar open-source project — FastAPI's rate-limiting middleware.">

	<!-- Section 1: When the Codebase Isn't Yours -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">When the Codebase Isn't Yours</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Tutorials 1 through 3 built a project from scratch. You knew every line because you wrote every line. Real work is rarely like that. More often, you're dropped into an existing codebase — thousands of files, conventions you didn't choose, patterns you need to discover before you can follow them.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			This is where most AI-assisted coding falls apart. You paste code into Claude Code, ask it to "add a feature," and it generates something that looks right but doesn't follow the project's patterns, breaks existing tests, or conflicts with architectural decisions made months ago. The AI doesn't know what it doesn't know about the codebase.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			GSD handles this differently. Before any code is written, GSD's research and discuss phases map the codebase — discovering patterns, conventions, and constraints that must be respected. The planning phase then creates tasks that work <em>with</em> the existing architecture, not against it.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			In this tutorial, you'll use GSD to build a <strong class="text-heading">rate-limiting middleware</strong> for <a href="https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover transition-colors underline">FastAPI</a>, a popular Python web framework with 80k+ GitHub stars, extensive test coverage, and non-trivial internals. You'll see how GSD's workflow adapts when the challenge isn't writing code from scratch — it's understanding enough of someone else's code to extend it safely.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 2: Forking and Setting Up -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Setting the Stage</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Start by forking and cloning FastAPI. You'll work on a branch so the feature stays isolated:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Clone and set up"
			python={`git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/fastapi.git
cd fastapi
git checkout -b feature/rate-limiting

# Install dev dependencies
pip install -e ".[all]"
pip install -r requirements-tests.txt

# Start Claude Code — GSD commands are available
claude`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Run <code class="text-accent">/gsd-new-project</code> to initialize GSD. This is where things get interesting. Unlike Tutorial 2 where GSD initialized on a tiny project, here it's scanning a codebase with hundreds of files. GSD asks you about the project, then researches the structure:
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">GSD researches the codebase and discovers:</p>
			<div class="space-y-2">
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent shrink-0">&#9656;</span>
					<span class="text-text text-sm"><strong class="text-heading">Framework structure</strong> — ASGI-based, middleware uses <code class="text-accent text-xs">BaseHTTPMiddleware</code> or raw ASGI protocol</span>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent shrink-0">&#9656;</span>
					<span class="text-text text-sm"><strong class="text-heading">Dependency injection</strong> — <code class="text-accent text-xs">Depends()</code> pattern for per-route configuration</span>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent shrink-0">&#9656;</span>
					<span class="text-text text-sm"><strong class="text-heading">Test patterns</strong> — pytest with <code class="text-accent text-xs">TestClient</code>, tests mirror source structure in <code class="text-accent text-xs">tests/</code></span>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent shrink-0">&#9656;</span>
					<span class="text-text text-sm"><strong class="text-heading">Existing middleware</strong> — CORS, GZip, TrustedHost already implemented as reference patterns</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			This research phase is the key difference from greenfield work. GSD doesn't just ask "what do you want to build?" — it asks "what does this codebase expect?" The conventions it discovers become constraints on the plan. Your rate limiter won't be built from first principles; it'll be built to fit FastAPI's existing patterns.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 3: Research Phase -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Research: Understanding the Architecture</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Before discussing the feature, GSD needs to understand how FastAPI's middleware system works. During the discuss phase, GSD digs into the existing middleware implementations. Here's what it finds by reading <code class="text-accent">fastapi/middleware/</code> and the ASGI internals:
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">Key findings from GSD's research:</p>
			<pre class="text-text font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed"><code>FastAPI Middleware Architecture
==============================

1. Two middleware patterns coexist:
   - BaseHTTPMiddleware (simple, request/response model)
   - Pure ASGI middleware (lower-level, better performance)
   → Existing middleware uses pure ASGI pattern

2. Middleware is added via app.add_middleware():
   - CORSMiddleware, GZipMiddleware, TrustedHostMiddleware
   - Each takes config params in __init__
   - Each follows the same dispatch pattern

3. Dependency injection (Depends):
   - Can provide per-route overrides
   - Runs AFTER middleware, not before
   - Useful for route-specific rate limit config

4. Test patterns:
   - tests/test_middleware_*.py naming convention
   - TestClient from starlette.testclient
   - Async tests via pytest-anyio when needed

5. OpenAPI integration:
   - 429 responses should appear in OpenAPI schema
   - Use responses parameter on route decorators</code></pre>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			This research surfaces a critical insight: <strong class="text-heading">middleware runs before dependency injection</strong>. That means the rate limiter's core check must live in middleware (to catch requests early), but per-route configuration needs a different mechanism. GSD flags this in the discussion as an architectural constraint that shapes the plan.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			If you'd skipped research and jumped straight to coding, you'd have discovered this constraint halfway through implementation — after building a dependency-injection-based rate limiter that can't actually intercept requests early enough. The research phase catches these misunderstandings when they're free to fix.
		</p>
	</section>

