	<!-- Section 7: Plan 2 — Middleware Integration -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Plan 2: ASGI Middleware Integration</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Plan 2 runs with a fresh context. It reads the plan and the current code — which now includes the token bucket from Plan 1. The goal: wrap the rate limiter in an ASGI middleware that follows FastAPI's existing patterns.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			This is where respecting the codebase matters most. GSD's plan specifies: "Follow the same pattern as <code class="text-accent">CORSMiddleware</code> — pure ASGI class, config via <code class="text-accent">__init__</code>, added via <code class="text-accent">app.add_middleware()</code>." The plan doesn't just say what to build; it says how to build it so it looks like it belongs.
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="fastapi/middleware/ratelimit.py — Middleware class (added below TokenBucket)"
			python={`from starlette.requests import Request
from starlette.responses import Response
from starlette.types import ASGIApp, Receive, Scope, Send
from typing import Callable


class RateLimitMiddleware:
    """ASGI middleware for rate limiting.

    Usage:
        app.add_middleware(
            RateLimitMiddleware,
            rate=10.0,        # 10 tokens per second
            capacity=100,     # burst capacity
        )
    """

    def __init__(
        self,
        app: ASGIApp,
        rate: float = 10.0,
        capacity: int = 100,
        storage: RateLimitStorage | None = None,
        key_func: Callable[[Request], str] | None = None,
    ) -> None:
        self.app = app
        self.bucket = TokenBucket(rate=rate, capacity=capacity, storage=storage)
        self.key_func = key_func or self._default_key

    @staticmethod
    def _default_key(request: Request) -> str:
        if request.client:
            return request.client.host
        return "anonymous"

    async def __call__(
        self, scope: Scope, receive: Receive, send: Send
    ) -> None:
        if scope["type"] != "http":
            await self.app(scope, receive, send)
            return

        request = Request(scope)
        key = self.key_func(request)
        allowed, retry_after = self.bucket.consume(key)

        if not allowed:
            response = Response(
                content="Rate limit exceeded",
                status_code=429,
                headers={"Retry-After": str(int(retry_after) + 1)},
            )
            await response(scope, receive, send)
            return

        await self.app(scope, receive, send)`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Notice the pattern: check the scope type, extract request info, make the decision, either forward to the next middleware or return a response. This is exactly how FastAPI's existing middleware works. A developer familiar with the codebase would recognize this immediately.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The middleware tests follow FastAPI's conventions — <code class="text-accent">tests/test_middleware_ratelimit.py</code> using <code class="text-accent">TestClient</code>:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="tests/test_middleware_ratelimit.py"
			python={`from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.middleware.ratelimit import RateLimitMiddleware
from starlette.testclient import TestClient


def create_app(rate: float = 10.0, capacity: int = 2) -> FastAPI:
    app = FastAPI()
    app.add_middleware(RateLimitMiddleware, rate=rate, capacity=capacity)

    @app.get("/")
    async def root():
        return {"message": "ok"}

    return app


def test_allows_normal_requests():
    client = TestClient(create_app(capacity=5))
    response = client.get("/")
    assert response.status_code == 200


def test_returns_429_when_rate_limited():
    client = TestClient(create_app(rate=0.1, capacity=1))
    client.get("/")  # Consume the one token
    response = client.get("/")
    assert response.status_code == 429
    assert "Retry-After" in response.headers


def test_retry_after_header_is_present():
    client = TestClient(create_app(rate=1.0, capacity=1))
    client.get("/")
    response = client.get("/")
    retry = int(response.headers["Retry-After"])
    assert retry >= 1


def test_custom_key_function():
    def api_key_func(request):
        return request.headers.get("X-API-Key", "anonymous")

    app = FastAPI()
    app.add_middleware(
        RateLimitMiddleware, rate=0.1, capacity=1, key_func=api_key_func
    )

    @app.get("/")
    async def root():
        return {"message": "ok"}

    client = TestClient(app)
    # Different API keys get separate buckets
    client.get("/", headers={"X-API-Key": "key-a"})
    response = client.get("/", headers={"X-API-Key": "key-b"})
    assert response.status_code == 200`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Plan 2 verification: all middleware tests pass, plus the core tests from Plan 1 still pass. GSD commits atomically.
		</p>
