	<!-- Section 8: Plan 3 — Per-Route Config + OpenAPI -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Plan 3: Per-Route Configuration + OpenAPI</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The final feature plan adds per-route rate limit overrides and OpenAPI documentation. Remember the constraint from research: middleware runs before dependency injection. The solution is a decorator that attaches rate limit metadata to the route, which the middleware reads from the ASGI scope:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Per-route rate limit decorator"
			python={`from functools import wraps
from typing import Callable


def rate_limit(rate: float, capacity: int) -> Callable:
    """Override the global rate limit for a specific route.

    Usage:
        @app.get("/heavy-endpoint")
        @rate_limit(rate=1.0, capacity=5)
        async def heavy_operation():
            ...
    """
    def decorator(func: Callable) -> Callable:
        func._rate_limit = {"rate": rate, "capacity": capacity}

        @wraps(func)
        async def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
            return await func(*args, **kwargs)
        wrapper._rate_limit = func._rate_limit
        return wrapper
    return decorator`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The middleware checks for route-level overrides before applying the global limit. And for OpenAPI, routes with rate limiting include a 429 response in their schema:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Usage example — global + per-route rate limits"
			python={`from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.middleware.ratelimit import RateLimitMiddleware, rate_limit

app = FastAPI()

# Global limit: 100 requests/second, burst of 200
app.add_middleware(RateLimitMiddleware, rate=100.0, capacity=200)


@app.get("/")
async def homepage():
    """Uses the global rate limit."""
    return {"message": "welcome"}


@app.get(
    "/expensive-operation",
    responses={429: {"description": "Rate limit exceeded"}},
)
@rate_limit(rate=1.0, capacity=5)
async def expensive():
    """Stricter limit: 1 req/sec, burst of 5."""
    return {"result": "computed"}


@app.get("/health")
@rate_limit(rate=1000.0, capacity=1000)
async def health():
    """Effectively no rate limit on health checks."""
    return {"status": "ok"}`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			The <code class="text-accent">responses=&#123;429: ...&#125;</code> parameter tells FastAPI's OpenAPI generator to include a 429 response in the schema. Anyone reading the API docs knows which endpoints are rate-limited and what the error looks like. This follows FastAPI's existing pattern — it's how other error responses are documented throughout the codebase.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 9: Plan 4 — Integration & Regression -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Plan 4: The Regression Gate</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			This plan doesn't write new code. It runs the full integration test suite — both your new tests <em>and</em> FastAPI's existing tests. This is the plan that doesn't exist in greenfield tutorials but is <strong class="text-heading">essential</strong> for existing codebases.
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Plan 4 verification"
			python={`# Run new rate limiting tests
pytest tests/test_ratelimit_core.py tests/test_middleware_ratelimit.py -v
# 6 + 4 = 10 passed

