# ...
# 1847 passed, 23 skipped in 142.31s

# Verify OpenAPI schema includes 429 responses
python -c "
from fastapi.testclient import TestClient
# ... (schema verification)
print('OpenAPI schema: 429 responses documented')
"`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			1,847 existing tests still pass. Your 10 new tests pass. The OpenAPI schema correctly documents rate-limited endpoints. <strong class="text-heading">This is the proof that you've added a feature without breaking anything</strong> — and it only exists because GSD's plan included a regression gate.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			In a typical AI-assisted workflow, you'd run your new tests (which pass) and declare victory. The 1,847 existing tests would run in CI thirty minutes later, and you'd discover you broke the CORS middleware interaction. Plan 4 catches that before you push.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 10: What's Different About Existing Codebases -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">What's Different About Existing Codebases</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Having built the same kind of feature in both a greenfield project (Tutorials 1-3) and an existing codebase (this tutorial), here's what's qualitatively different:
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Research is load-bearing</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">In greenfield, you choose the patterns. In existing code, you discover them. The research phase found that middleware runs before DI, that existing middleware uses the pure ASGI pattern, and that tests follow a specific naming convention. Skipping research means building something that doesn't fit — which means rework or rejection in code review.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Conventions are constraints, not suggestions</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">The rate limiter could have used <code class="text-accent text-xs">BaseHTTPMiddleware</code> — it's simpler. But existing middleware uses the ASGI pattern. Following the convention means your code is immediately readable to anyone who knows the codebase. Breaking it means your code looks foreign, even if it works.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Existing tests are your safety net</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">In greenfield, you write all the tests. In existing code, there are already 1,847 tests that implicitly define "correct behavior." Running them after your changes is non-negotiable. GSD makes this a first-class plan, not an afterthought.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Isolation before integration</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Plan 1 built and tested the token bucket with zero FastAPI imports. If the algorithm had a bug, you'd find it in a 0.12-second test run — not buried under middleware wiring and ASGI plumbing. In a large codebase, isolating your new logic makes debugging dramatically faster.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">The discuss phase does more work</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">In greenfield, discuss resolves your preferences. In existing code, discuss reconciles your intent with the codebase's constraints. "Where does state live?" had a right answer dictated by the architecture, not just a preference. GSD surfaced that before planning, not during execution.</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

